The reason I’m saying all this is that the problem runs deeper than “white cishet people think our trauma is a fun break”, although that is very much true. I just want to keep in mind the environment that puts people there.

I still think that it’s important to remind people the ugly truth about these fantasies, especially since minorities are the ones who suffer most from others ignoring it. People should be discouraged from acting on these ideas or diminishing other's experiences.
Also what kind of society tells you that you can’t take a break guilt free unless you are forced to?

// Tw suicide mention

What kind of life does someone have that they think prison is a break? How much do you want to escape your life that anything short of suicide is an improvement?
But these people don’t really want to run away. They want their lives to be better. As I’m sure the people romanticizing institutionalization do.

I feel like this is similar to the idea of running away. A lot of people fantasize about it, but anyone who has been kicked out of their home knows how difficult it is. These people may want to say “you don’t know how traumatic it is, why do you want to willingly do that?”

Despite the doctors telling me that I wasn’t trying hard enough, blaming me for my trauma, and telling me I was a lost cause, I still hesitated to leave. I had finally gotten an escape from my abusive family. I knew someone else there who was there to escape their family.

As someone who has been institutionalized, this is true. These experiences can be and often are traumatizing. But I also want to ask why these experiences seem like a vacation. I know for me, my time in a psych ward was both traumatic and a sort of break. https://t.co/N0xvy6vjBL
